{"title_page": "COVID-19 pandemic in the Falkland Islands", "text_new": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in the Falkland Islands}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 Coronavirus pandemic in the Falkland Islands\n| map1            = Falkland Islands-corona-2020-04-09.png\n| places          = \n| legend1         = Location of the COVID-19 outbreak\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Falkland Islands]]\n| first_case      = [[RAF Mount Pleasant]]\n| arrival_date    = 3 April 2020\n| origin          = [[United Kingdom]]\n| confirmed_cases = 13<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fig.gov.fk/covid-19|title=COVID-19 Update - 1 May 2020|website=Falkland Island Government|access-date=4 May 2020}}</ref><!--<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.facebook.com/FalkIandsGov/posts/|title=Press Statement 27 April 2020|access-date=28 April 2020|website=Falkland Island Government via Facebook}}</ref>--> (2020-05-03)\n| suspected_cases = \n| recovery_cases  = 13\n| deaths          = \n| website         = [https://fig.gov.fk/covid-19 COVID-19 @ F.I.G.] \n}}\nThe [[COVID-19 pandemic]]  was confirmed to have reached to the [[Falkland Islands]] on 3 April 2020.<ref name=\"first\"/> On 30 April, all patients recovered.<ref name=\"recovered\"/>\n\n==Background==\nThe Falkland Islands Infectious Diseases Plan set out stages for the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] response. The Falkland Islands has carried out robust preparations for COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.mercopress.com/2020/03/21/falklands-moves-to-next-covid-19-response-march-26-referendum-postponed-for-six-months|title=Falklands moves to next COVID-19 response; March 26 referendum postponed for six months \u2014 MercoPress}}</ref> It was announced that measures may include:\n*Restrictions on all non-essential travel both internationally and locally.\n*Possible changes in attendance to schools and nurseries, which will be implemented gradually in the next few weeks.\n*Revised arrangements on the use of [[Falkland Islands Government Air Service]] (FIGAS) and [[Concordia Bay]].\n*Changes to the delivery of health services. This includes changes to the way [[King Edward VII Memorial Hospital]] (KEMH) will operate.  Medical visits to [[Camp (Falkland Islands)|Camp]] will also be increased.\n*Contacting those vulnerable people we know of and providing further advice.\n*A range of measures to support the Falkland Islands economy, including businesses and staff, are being developed and will be announced in due course.\n\nThere are no facilities to test for the virus on the Falklands and it takes around 10 days to get test results back from Britain, which is almost 8,000 miles away.<ref name=\"time_falklands\">{{Cite news|url=https://time.com/5811309/coronavirus-falklands/|title=Isolation Helped These Islands Delay a COVID-19 Outbreak. Now, Being Remote Could Be Their Biggest Problem|website=Time|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> On 23 March, the [[Government of Argentina|Argentinian Government]] offered the [[List of ambassadors of the United Kingdom to Brazil|British ambassador to Brazil]] medical supplies including Covid 19 tests,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.infobae.com/america/agencias/2020/03/23/argentina-ofrece-a-gran-bretana-ayuda-para-los-habitantes-de-las-islas-malvinas-por-coronavirus/|title=Argentina ofrece a Gran Breta\u00f1a ayuda para los habitantes de las Islas Malvinas por coronavirus (in Spanish)|website=infobae|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> but the Falklands has as of 27 March not followed up on the offer.<ref name=\"time_falklands\" /> The Falklands has received the equipment to test locally, and will be in operation in the first week of May.<ref name=\"restrictions_eased\"/>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{Medical cases chart\n|numwidth=wmd\n\n|disease=COVID-19\n|location=Falkland Islands\n|outbreak=2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic\n\n<!-- |togglesbar=\n<div class=\"nomobile\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n{{Medical cases chart/Month toggle button|mar}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Month toggle button|apr}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Month toggle button|l15}}\n</div> -->\n\n|data=\n<!--date;deaths;recoveries;total_cases;;;total_cases;+%;-->\n2020-04-03; 0;  0;  1;;;  1;n.a.\n;            ;   ;  1;;;  1;collapsed=y;id=apr\n2020-04-05; 0;  0;  2;;;  2;+100%\n;            ;   ;  2;;;  2;collapsed=y;id=apr\n2020-04-08; 0;  1;  5;;;  5;+150%\n;            ;  1;  5;;;  5;collapsed=y;id=apr\n2020-04-14; 0;  1; 11;;; 11;+120%\n;            ;  1; 11;;; 11;collapsed=y;id=apr\n2020-04-17; 0;  4; 11;;; 11;=\n;            ;  4; 11;;; 11;collapsed=y;id=apr\n2020-04-21; 0; 11; 12;;; 12;+9%\n;            ; 11; 12;;; 12;collapsed=y;id=apr\n2020-04-24; 0; 11; 13;;; 13;+8.3%\n;            ; 11; 13;;; 13;collapsed=y;id=apr\n2020-04-30; 0; 13; 13;;; 13;=\n\n|caption=Data sourced from [https://fig.gov.fk/covid-19 fig.gov.fk]<br>\n<small>The testing lag often results gaps in the chart, because the results were still pending.</small>\n}}\n===March===\nOn 19 March, around 238 people were flown off the islands on a plane bound for [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]], [[Argentina]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/world/1257737/coronavirus-live-update-Falkland-islands-south-America-covid-19|title=Coronavirus panic: Falkland Islands 'strongly advises' tourists LEAVE before virus hits|first=Bill|last=McLoughlin|date=March 19, 2020|website=Express.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe Falkland Islands government confirmed it has had contact with the [[United Kingdom]] concerning the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.mercopress.com/2020/03/21/london-s-support-for-falklands-to-deal-with-the-impacts-of-the-pandemic|title=London's support for Falklands to deal with the impacts of the pandemic|publisher=Merco Press|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\nThe government on the islands advised tourists and foreigners to leave the archipelago as it cannot guarantee further flights leaving the islands, whilst cruise ships reaching the Falklands would only be allowed to dock if passengers had been on board for at least 10 days and if none were suffering from symptoms of COVID-19.\nTravel between the islands of the Falklands is heavily restricted. Social distancing measures are in place.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://fig.gov.fk/covid-19#what-is-social-distancing-and-why-is-it-important-20-march-2020|title=Latest Updates|website=Falkland Islands Government|access-date=30 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, Argentina said it had reached out to Britain's ambassador in [[Buenos Aires]] to offer material support to the inhabitants of the Falkland Islands hit by the coronavirus outbreak.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sigal |first1=Lucila |title=Argentina offers coronavirus aid to UK citizens in Falklands |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-falklands/argentina-offers-coronavirus-aid-to-uk-citizens-in-falklands-idUSL1N2BG2LX |accessdate=16 April 2020 |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, as a precaution, the islands' government has closed all schools and nurseries until 4 May.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.mercopress.com/2020/03/26/falkland-islands-new-stage-in-government-covid-19-response|title=Falkland Islands: New stage in Government COVID-19 response|publisher=Merco Press|date=26 March 2020|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, it was confirmed that a child was critically ill with suspected COVID-19 and was being treated at a small hospital in [[Stanley, Falkland Islands|Stanley]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-falkland-islands-brace-for-first-covid-19-case-11964898|title=Coronavirus: Falkland Islands brace for first COVID-19 case|website=Sky News}}</ref>\n\n===April===\nOn '''3 April''', the first case in the Falkland Islands was officially confirmed.<ref name=\"first\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-british-serviceperson-is-falkland-islands-first-case-of-covid-19-11968338|title=Coronavirus: British serviceperson is Falkland Islands' first case of COVID-19|website=Sky News|date=4 April 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020|last=Haynes|first=Deborah}}</ref> All schools and nurseries were closed and all workers not deemed critical  told to stay at home.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/04/coronavirus-case-confirmed-falkland-islands-12507195/|title=British serviceperson is first case of coronavirus in Falkland Islands|website=Metro UK|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April, a second case was confirmed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/FalklandsinUK/status/1246867711298351106|title=Breaking: 5:4:20 A second positive test result for coronavirus #COVID19 has been confirmed by CMO Dr Edwards in the #Falklands #FalklandIslands. The patient is based at the #BFSAI Mount Pleasant Complex, where they have been in isolation with a range of COVID19 like symptoms.pic.twitter.com/2MWHgoNUaR|last=FalklandsinUK|date=2020-04-05|website=@FalklandsinUK|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April, there were five cases and one recovery, all serving at the [[RAF Mount Pleasant|Mount Pleasant Complex]]. 137 people have been tested thus far.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fig.gov.fk/covid-19#covid-19-public-update-8-april-2020|title=COVID 19 Public Update - 8 April 2020|website=Falkland Island Government|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 April, there were 11 cases and one recovery.<ref name=\"upd-04-14\">{{cite news |title=COVID-19 Public Update PM - 14 April 2020 |url=https://fig.gov.fk/covid-19#covid-19-public-update-pm-14-april-2020 |accessdate=14 April 2020 |publisher=Falklands Islands Government |date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 15 April, 255 samples had been processed. Additional measures were put in place, and journeys from and to Mount Pleasant Complex needed to be approved. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fig.gov.fk/covid-19|title=COVID-19 Public Update - 15 April 2020|access-date=16 April 2020|website=Falklands Islands Government}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 April, a set of measures was announced for individuals and business and includes among others, a job retention scheme, unemployment subsidy, non-repayable grants to businesses. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fig.gov.fk/covid-19#government-unveils-comprehensive-covid-19-support-package-17-april|title=Government unveils comprehensive COVID-19 support package - 17 April|access-date=18 April 2020|website=Falklands Islands Government}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 April, it was announced that the Falkland Islands will be able to test for COVID-19 next week when the testing machines will arrive. 337 samples have been send to the United Kingdom thus far.<ref name=\"local_testing\">{{Cite news|url=https://en.mercopress.com/2020/04/23/falklands-should-be-ready-next-week-to-test-swabs-in-the-islands|title=Falklands should be ready next week to test swabs in the Islands|access-date=25 April 2020|website=Merco Press}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 April, it was announced that the fishing industry is facing a difficult time due to the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://en.mercopress.com/2020/04/24/falklands-faces-fishing-markets-paralyzed-on-covid-19-impact|title=Falklands faces fishing markets paralyzed on COVID-19 impact|website=Merco Press|access-date=25 April 2020}}</ref> Between 50 and 60% of [[Gross domestic product|GDP]] of the Falklands depends on fishing.<ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.falklands.gov.fk/self-sufficiency/|title = Self-sufficiency|website = The Falkland Islands Government|accessdate = 25 April 2020}}</ref>\n<div style=\"clear:both;\"> </div>\n\nOn 27 April, the prices of wool had dropped 50% compared to last year. The prices had already been under decline, but the remaining crash was caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.penguin-news.com/index.php/headlines/all-headlines/18-rural/172-wool-prices-down-50-since-early-last-year|title=Wool prices down 50% since early last year|issue=week 18<!-- weekly publication-->|website=Penguin News|access-date=1 May 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 April, it was announced that price of electricity per unit for all consumers will be decreased from 23p to 18p from 1 May onwards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fig.gov.fk/covid-19#covid-19-public-update-29-april-2020|title=COVID-19 Public Update - 29 April 2020|website=The Falkland Islands Government|access-date=29 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn '''30 April''', it was announced that all 13 cases have recovered.<ref name=\"recovered\">{{Cite web|url=https://fig.gov.fk/covid-19#covid-19-public-update-30-april-2020|title=COVID-19 Public Update - 30 April 2020|website=Falkland Islands Government|access-date=1 May 2020}}</ref>\n\n===May===\nOn 1 May, an easing of restrictions was announced: schools, businesses will reopen on 11 May. The travel restriction between Stanley and Mount Pleasant will remain in effect.<ref name=\"restrictions_eased\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fig.gov.fk/covid-19#government-easing-some-covid-19-restrictions-1-may-2020|title=Government easing some restrictions - 1 May 2020|website=Falkland Islands Government|access-date=1 May 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\nChronology of the number of active cases\n{{Graph:Chart\n| type = line\n| linewidth = 1\n| showSymbols = 1\n| yType= integer\n| width = 600\n| colors = #ff6347, cyan, black\n| xAxisTitle = Date\n| xAxisAngle = -40\n| xType = date\n| xAxisFormat = %e %b\n| x = 2 April 2020, 3 April 2020, 4 April 2020, 5 April 2020, 6 April 2020, 7 April 2020, 8 April 2020, 9 April 2020, 10 April 2020, 11 April 2020, 12 April 2020, 13 April 2020, 14 April 2020, 15 April 2020, 16 April 2020, 17 April 2020, 18 April 2020, 19 April 2020, 20 April 2020, 21 April 2020, 22 April 2020, 23 April 2020, 24 April 2020, 25 April 2020, 26 April 2020, 27 April 2020, 28 April 2020, 29 April 2020, 30 April 